# Azure deploy from Cursor

When the user asks to deploy to Azure, run the project deploy script — do not invent a one-off az sequence.

## Prerequisites

1. Azure CLI installed (`az --version`)
2. Logged in: `az login`
3. `.env.deploy` at repo root (copy from `.env.deploy.example`) with `PG_ADMIN_PASSWORD` and `JWT_SECRET` set

## Deploy command

From the repo root:

```bash
chmod +x scripts/deploy.sh   # once, if needed
./scripts/deploy.sh
```

| Flag | When to use |
|------|-------------|
| `--bootstrap` | Explicit first-time deploy (infra → images → redeploy) |
| `--skip-tests` | Hotfix deploy when tests are already green |
| `--dry-run` | Show steps without calling Azure |
| `--tag TAG` | Pin image tag (default: short git SHA) |

The script auto-bootstraps if no ACR exists in the resource group.

## After deploy

Read the printed `frontendUrl`, or:

```bash
az deployment group show -g mybetrecord-rg -n main \
  --query properties.outputs.frontendUrl.value -o tsv
```

## Permissions

The deploy script needs **network** access for `az acr build` and Azure API calls. Request `full_network` (or `all`) when running it from the agent.

## Do not commit

Never commit `.env.deploy` or paste secrets into chat. If secrets are missing, tell the user to fill `.env.deploy` locally.

## CI/CD

GitHub Actions uses the same script on push to `main` (see `.github/workflows/ci-cd.yml`).
